    <stitle>RECONDITIONING ROTORS - INSPECTION - POLISHED ROTORS</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="inspect" graphiccount="1">
        <title>POLISHED ROTORS</title>
        <para>A polished rotor can be identified by the mirror-like finish on the braking surface (
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0401821">Figure 21
                <xref refid="f0401821"/>
            </hotlnk>
            ).
        </para>
        <figure id="f0401821" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0401821" filename="../figg04/G0401821.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="272px" resolution="72"/>
            <caption>Figure 21. Polished Rotor</caption>
        </figure>
        <para>This problem is easily solved by removing the gloss with 80-grit emery cloth. If the problem consistently
            recurs, brake pads should be checked for proper friction rating. Glazed brake pads may be repaired by
            removing the glazed surface.
        </para>
        <para>Sanding the rotor is also recommended when replacing brake pads, if the braking surfaces are polished.
        </para>
    </svcproc>
